    "summary": "Urukagina (also transliterated as Uruinimgina), king of the Sumerian city-state of Lagash around 2380–2360 BC, is notable for issuing what historians consider the earliest known social reform decrees in recorded history. His reforms, inscribed on clay cones and tablets, addressed abuses perpetrated by priests, officials, and tax collectors against the common people of Lagash, and they explicitly framed these reforms in terms of justice and divine mandate.\n\nThe specific abuses Urukagina claimed to have abolished include excessive taxation, the misappropriation of temple property by officials, corruption in the administration of estates, and mistreatment of poorer citizens by the powerful. His decrees also addressed protections for widows, orphans, and the poor — groups that routinely appear in ancient Near Eastern legal texts as vulnerable to exploitation. The language of the reforms is notably moral in tone, invoking the god Ningirsu as the authority behind the king's mandate to protect the weak from the strong.\n\nUrukagina's reforms did not endure long; his reign was brought to an end by the military conquest of Lagash by Lugalzagesi of Umma, who apparently reversed many of the reforms. Despite their brief duration, the decrees are historically significant as the earliest surviving record of a ruler claiming a mandate to protect citizens from governmental abuse — a concept that would recur throughout ancient Near Eastern political thought and eventually influence the legal traditions of Babylon and beyond.",
